Question: Through which channels can a whistleblower submit a breach report to
  European banking supervision, and what role does the Independent
  Investigating Unit play once a suspected breach has been referred to
  it?
Example answer: Reports may be submitted via an ECB reporting channel implemented as a
  web form on the ECB's banking supervision website, which directly
  forwards the report to the Enforcement and Sanctions Division, by
  other means such as letters, or via mechanisms in place at NCAs to
  receive reports from whistleblowers. Once a suspected breach is
  referred to the Independent Investigating Unit, the unit may
  exercise the powers granted to the ECB by the SSM Regulation to
  request documents, examine relevant books and records, request
  explanations, conduct interviews and on-site inspections, and assess
  on the basis of the evidence whether there is reasonable suspicion
  of possible breaches; if so, it may initiate sanctioning proceedings
  by addressing a statement of objections to the supervised entity.
  (ECB Supervisory Manual, pages 106, 108)
Predicted answer: Whistle‑blower channels: (i) an ECB reporting channel via a web form
  on the ECB banking supervision website that directly forwards
  reports to the Enforcement and Sanctions Division; (ii) other means
  of reporting to the ECB (e.g. letters); and (iii) reporting
  mechanisms operated by NCAs.    Role of the Independent
  Investigating Unit: upon referral the IU may initiate an
  investigation, exercise investigatory powers under the SSMR (request
  documents, examine books and records, obtain explanations, hold
  interviews and conduct on‑site inspections), instruct NCAs to use
  national investigatory powers, assess the available evidence and
  grant the right to be heard, and, where appropriate, prepare a
  proposal to the Supervisory Board for a draft decision imposing
  administrative penalties or request the relevant NCA to open
  national sanctioning or criminal referral proceedings (ECB
  Supervisory Manual, pp. 107–110).
