Question: How are the responsibilities for crisis management split between the
  ECB and NCAs depending on whether the institution in difficulty is
  significant or less significant?
Example answer: For significant institutions, the JSTs in close cooperation with the
  Business Model, Capital & Crisis Division are responsible for crisis
  preparedness and management across different phases, with the Crisis
  Team providing expert support to the JSTs on processes in the
  applicable legal framework, the early identification of crisis
  situations, the assessment and operationalisation of recovery plans
  and resolution-related consultations. For less significant
  institutions, the responsibility for managing crisis cases lies with
  the NCAs and other relevant authorities at the national level, while
  the ECB plays a coordinating role when the situation becomes
  critical at the point of non-viability and remains the competent
  authority for taking decisions on common procedures such as the
  withdrawal of banking authorisations. (ECB Supervisory Manual, pages
  99, 115)
Predicted answer: (i) For significant institutions (SIs): the ECB is the direct
  supervisor and thus is responsible for their supervision and crisis
  management. (ii) For less significant institutions (LSIs): NCAs
  retain responsibility for managing crisis cases (including
  supervisory decisions, early‑intervention and
  failing‑or‑likely‑to‑fail decisions), while the ECB exercises
  oversight, coordinates when situations become critical and may take
  decisions on common procedures (e.g. qualifying holdings, withdrawal
  of authorisation, licensing of a bridge bank) or, in specific cases
  (including at NCA request or if the institution becomes an SI), take
  over direct supervision. (ECB Supervisory Manual, pp. 6, 112, 116)
